testimonial: My husband was made redundant in the first week of lockdown.  This is not a negative situation as other opportunists will come soon.  Tom is now paid to be my carer and it has relieved so much pressure from us as I need  support with house work and cleaning.  There never seemed to be enough time in the day when we were both working/travelling and commuting to and from work.  I usually travel by public transport one and half hour each way to and from work.  This causes me so much anxiety and having this time out has enabled me to identify what areas of life need changing.

testimonial: I have a chronic illness and the lockdown has affected me physically in a bad way, which has a knock on effect with my mental health. Physically I am feeling much worse than I did before lockdown - I didn’t realise how the little I *could* do had such a huge impact on how much my chronic illness affects me. I’m managing mentally to keep mostly on top of it, but some days when the pain is stronger, it gets on top of me. Exercise outside of my home doesn’t feel safe (I’m also in a high risk group) and I’m unable to support my body in other ways that I used to - chiro, walking in swimming pools, light gym workouts, massages, etc - for very obvious reasons so it all feels unnerving and is sometimes a struggle.

testimonial: I’m worried about the impact on my son- he is one and was meant to start nursery. The lack of social engagement is a little worrying. I also feel very disconnected from friends and extended family as all of my time is work/housework/childcare. Our wedding is also going to have to be cancelled which is putting strain on us emotionally and financially. On a positive my son is getting so much more time with his dad which is benefitting both of them. And I think my partner is better understanding why I was sometimes losing my mind during maternity leave! We live far from family and I’m worried about my parents. I don’t think my partner really thinks much about anything other than how he is doing. The emotional burden is on me.
